                <ArticleTitle>Meniscal repair vs. meniscectomy: a randomized controlled trial.</ArticleTitle>
                <Pagination>
                    <StartPage>300</StartPage>
                    <EndPage>312</EndPage>
                    <MedlinePgn>300-312</MedlinePgn>
                </Pagination>
                <ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.arthro.2024.02.003</ELocationID>
                <Abstract>
                    <AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Meniscal injuries are common and treatment selection remains controversial.</AbstractText>
                    <AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">We randomized 150 patients to meniscal repair or partial meniscectomy and followed them for 24 months.</AbstractText>
                    <AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Patients undergoing repair had higher functional scores at 24 months (p&lt;0.01).</AbstractText>
                    <AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Meniscal repair is superior to meniscectomy for reparable tears in active patients.</AbstractText>
                </Abstract>
